post_text:
“I have been a part of this community for a little over 2 years. I have seen the McKenzie Community go through a lot these last few years and I'm amazed at how they overcome anything thrown at them. The community really sticks together and perseveres together. They are there for each other in the good times and the hard times. There is nothing that stops them from what's important: The Community. I've included a poster that I made after having a conversation with my 3rd grade class, two years ago, talking about what makes this community so special. They came up with everything on the poster. Even at 8 and 9 years old, they know what is important!
We are McKenzie Strong! ❤” - McKenzie Vreeland

Share your #McKenzieStrong messages! You can send us a direct message with a photo to our Facebook account. We look forward to sharing them here!

post_text:
While we know the road ahead of us is long, we will celebrate all wins together. Today, I am happy to highlight that Friday, our own, Brent Caulley, GEAR-UP Coordinator by day and community hero after hours, was able to rescue and reunite us with our student devices.

For those who didn’t know, Brent is an Upper McKenzie Rural Fire Protection District firefighter who is tirelessly working to extinguish the Holiday Farm Fire.

While we have many items on our to-do list as we work to reconnect with our students, thank to Brent, his fire team, Leonard Meyer, Corey Culp and the many other #McKenzieStrong helpers we have one less hurdle to jump.

post_text:
The secretaries have been hard at work calling ALL families for registration, including the new ones! Please call to schedule your appointment for the WEEK of WELCOME if you do not have one yet, we do not want to miss anyone. Elementary office (541) 822-3315 / Middle-High office (541) 822-3313, either office can help you for all of your students.

We are going over your students' current registration form, scheduling an appointment to meet your student's new teacher (elementary) or meeting with the guide group advisor (middle/high) and answering a short survey. This is your registration for this school year. The appointments will be much like parent/teacher conferences in length. At the appointment you will pick up materials for your student to get started with Comprehensive Distance Learning (CDL). The first day of student instruction will begin on September 14, 2020.

We look forward to hearing from you!

post_text:
In conjunction with our community partner, the Organic Redneck Farm (located by the passing lane on the town side of Vida), the Family Resource Center (FRC) wants fruit to be accessible to all children in our community. Local families with children are invited to pick berries & fruit during August at the Organic Redneck Farm. Each family may pick up to ten pounds of berries with an additional $20 to spend on farm stand produce.

The first 50 familes with children that show up will get this amazing opportunity. Once per family please. The Organic Redneck Farm is open Wednesday thru Sunday from 10 am until 6 pm @ 44382 McKenzie Hwy, Leaburg, OR 97489 www.ogredneck.com Please read their COVID regulations.

If you are in need of resources including food, clothing and books for your children, the FRC may be able to help. Contact Cricket at cricket.clarke@mckenziesd.org

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1l-04FtVspJEKrfSWit3tv0omaq_EV-Xj/view?usp=sharing

GEAR UP McKenzie
July 27 at 12:16 PM ·

We would like to thank all the students and parents who made this possible for us this year, and we're hoping to grow upon this in the coming school year. Please remember that the FAFSA is the first step in getting many types of financial aid including the Oregon Promise Grant as well as many McKenzie Scholarships.
The FAFSA application will be open for upcoming seniors starting October 1st.

The McKenzie River Food Bank is open today June 9, 2020 from 3 PM to 6PM.
𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐫𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐨𝐝𝐚𝐲 we will also have the 𝐒𝐮𝐦𝐦𝐞𝐫 𝐅𝐨𝐨𝐝 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐠𝐫𝐚𝐦: This is lunches for children ages 1 through 18. You can pick them up at the Food Pantry today for the next 2 weeks. 𝐘𝐨𝐮 𝐝𝐨 𝐧𝐨𝐭 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐛𝐞 𝐚 𝐫𝐞𝐠𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐫 𝐩𝐚𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐲 𝐜𝐥𝐢𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐭𝐨 𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐫𝐞𝐬𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐜𝐞, 𝐣𝐮𝐬𝐭 𝐬𝐡𝐨𝐰 𝐮𝐩 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐲𝐨𝐮 𝐰𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐠𝐞𝐭 𝐟𝐨𝐨𝐝.
Our volunteers will shop for you and bring you your boxes. We are also asking that you stagger your arrival times as follows: 3 pm - 4 pm A - H, 4 pm - 5 pm I - P, 5 pm - 6 pm Q – Z.

Thanks,
Sue O'Brien
Manager McKenzie River Food Pantry

We've got spirit, yes we do! We've got spirit, how 'bout you?

It's the last week of school!

Wednesday Dress Up Day (6/10): SCHOOL COLORS- Let's end the school year sporting your McKenzie gear or rocking a crazy green and gold outfit.

Weekly Challenge: Random Acts of Kindness! This week, look for opportunities to show that you care by performing Random Acts of Kindness. Send in a story or a picture to let us know how you're helping others!

Student Spotlight: Share your hobbies, hidden talents, or let us know what you're doing for fun during this time of social distancing!

If you want your school spirit photos shared to the school’s livestream and facebook page, email them to Ms. Christensen at corey.christensen@mckenziesd.org

From Oregon Department of Education: "Oregon is the recipient of a grant to provide funds to children experiencing food insecurity during this Pandemic. The Oregon Department of Education Child Nutrition Programs is supporting The Pandemic Electronic Benefits Transfer (P-EBT) program by collecting data from schools. If your child is eligible, you will be contacted shortly by DHS. Instructions will be included to activate or refuse benefits."

All students 𝙚𝙣𝙧𝙤𝙡𝙡𝙚𝙙 at McKenzie are eligible due to our Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) which allows us to offer breakfast and lunch free of charge to students.

To help answer questions, see our website, Facebook page or follow these links for more information:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Am6pN2noLjx6a-LEih8w1LF3FBrohzzy/view?usp=sharing

Going on a field trip to Silver Falls State Park when I was in 8th grade, and being able to walk behind multiple giant waterfalls.

post_text:
𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐞 𝐋𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠: 𝐓𝐢𝐩𝐬 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐥𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐟𝐫𝐨𝐦 𝐡𝐨𝐦𝐞.

𝐌𝐚𝐤𝐞 𝐚 𝐩𝐥𝐚𝐧: The school and your teacher will prepare your lessons, but it'll be good if you'll plan how you'll be studying at home.
𝐓𝐚𝐤𝐞 𝐧𝐨𝐭𝐞𝐬: Notes will help you remember lessons as you watch/go through them. It will also be useful for reviewing later.
𝐓𝐚𝐤𝐞 𝐚 𝐛𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐤: Do your work in blocks to lessen the strain. After finishing one lesson, take a five-minute break before moving on.
𝐁𝐞 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐝 𝐨𝐟 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐞𝐯𝐞𝐦𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐬: Studying at home isn't easy. Reward yourself for each small success.
𝐃𝐨 𝐨𝐧𝐞 𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐭 𝐚 𝐭𝐢𝐦𝐞: Finish one lesson before moving to the next. Do one assignment before another. Lessen multitasking.
𝐊𝐞𝐞𝐩 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐞: Treat your day as if you're going to school. Get up, take a shower, have breakfast.

post_text:
Hello McKenzie families: In order to support our students in our Distance Learning Program, we would like to offer the checking out of Chromebooks from the school. In accordance with District policy, Chromebooks would be checked out from the school with the sole intent and purpose of students being able to do their school work from home. A contract will need to be signed and asset numbers recorded in order to borrow a school device.

We are offering curbside pickup at the school this Friday, April 3rd, 2020..

Time of Pickup is based on Last Name: A-H 9am-11am, I-P 11am-1pm, Q-Z 1pm-3pm.

If you are unable to utilize this curbside pickup please let us know and we will find another way to get devices to you as soon as possible. Email: Brent.caulley@mckenziesd.org

Please follow this link for complete details and the process for pick up: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BltqklObiXUt1yQWYnElc8w9v4fnV6rwcULIizZGrzE/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
𝐈𝐬 𝐦𝐲 𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐝 𝐬𝐚𝐟𝐞 𝐚𝐭 𝐬𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐨𝐥?

Viruses can be spread in schools. This is why 𝐢𝐭’𝐬 𝐢𝐦𝐩𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐩𝐞𝐨𝐩𝐥𝐞 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐬𝐲𝐦𝐩𝐭𝐨𝐦𝐬 (𝐟𝐞𝐯𝐞𝐫, 𝐜𝐨𝐮𝐠𝐡,
𝐬𝐡𝐨𝐫𝐭𝐧𝐞𝐬𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐛𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐭𝐡) 𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐲 𝐡𝐨𝐦𝐞. It is one of the most effective ways to minimize exposure.

Public health is everyone’s responsibility. Teach your child to regularly practice good hygiene measures,
such as:

• Handwashing with soap and water for at least 20 seconds, and
• Coughing and sneezing etiquette.

𝙎𝙝𝙤𝙪𝙡𝙙 𝙢𝙮 𝙘𝙝𝙞𝙡𝙙 𝙨𝙩𝙖𝙮 𝙝𝙤𝙢𝙚?

𝙏𝙝𝙚 𝙢𝙖𝙞𝙣 𝙨𝙮𝙢𝙥𝙩𝙤𝙢𝙨 𝙤𝙛 𝘾𝙊𝙑𝙄𝘿-19 𝙖𝙧𝙚 𝙘𝙤𝙪𝙜𝙝, 𝙛𝙚𝙫𝙚𝙧 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙨𝙝𝙤𝙧𝙩𝙣𝙚𝙨𝙨 𝙤𝙛 𝙗𝙧𝙚𝙖𝙩𝙝. 𝙄𝙛 𝙮𝙤𝙪𝙧 𝙘𝙝𝙞𝙡𝙙 𝙢𝙚𝙧𝙚𝙡𝙮 𝙝𝙖𝙨 𝙖
𝙧𝙪𝙣𝙣𝙮 𝙣𝙤𝙨𝙚, 𝙮𝙤𝙪𝙧 𝙘𝙝𝙞𝙡𝙙 𝙢𝙖𝙮 𝙖𝙩𝙩𝙚𝙣𝙙 𝙨𝙘𝙝𝙤𝙤𝙡.

Many school district policies state that a child should be fever
free for 24 hours before they return to school. If your child has cough, fever and shortness of breath and
you are concerned about possible COVID-19, call your local health department or health care provider.
They will help you decide if you need an appointment. If so, they can help you plan a way to enter a
clinic in a way that avoids potentially infecting others.

post_text: In hopes of increasing communication and supporting our wonderful teachers, COrE (a volunteer group, formerly PTA) is organizing room parents for each elementary classroom. To facilitate this, they would like to create a contact list for each grade. Participation in this is voluntary but if you would like to receive updates on class activities and ways you can help our students, please provide your email address and phone number for text messages. Also, if there are ways you would like to help, or if you have any questions about COrE or our other projects, please contact them at core@mckenziesd.org. COrE meets on the second Tuesday of each month at 6:30pm in the HS Meeting Room.

post_text: Recently, cougar sightings have increased in our area. We have been made aware of a sighting very close to campus and have spoken with the Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife. Staff have been made aware of the sightings and we have discussed best practices in how to handle cougar encounters. As the seasons are changing and days are growing shorter, we encourage families to be careful at bus stops in the mornings and evenings. To learn more about what to do should you encounter a cougar please follow the link: https://www.dfw.state.or.us/wildlife/living_with/docs/CougarBroch.pdf
